<ce:para>Designing the structure of enantioselective adsorbents is a difficult task. In this work we propose a simple theoretical method of optimization of selectivity in adsorption on a model chiral surface composed of inert and active sites. Our approach is based on using the molecular footprints of the adsorbing enantiomers to find the optimal arrangement of active sites on the surface. In particular, we use a Monte Carlo search algorithm to predict the spatial distribution of active sites leading to the highest enantioselectivity. Additionally, we present the results of grand canonical Monte Carlo simulations performed for the equilibrium adsorption of enantiomers from a racemic mixture on the surfaces obtained using the MC approach. The optimal pattern of the active sites is dependent on the footprint of the chiral molecule as well as on the pressure under which the separation is performed. © 2007 American Chemical Society.</ce:para>
